05354nam a22009135i 9780812293692DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979744769  a97808122936927 a10.9783/97808122936922doi  a(DE-B1597)481215  a(OCoLC)971365647  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ799.I7bK47 2017 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a155.5/1822231 aKhosravi, Shahram, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrecarious Lives :bWaiting and Hope in Iran /cShahram Khosravi. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Ethnography00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration and Dates -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Precarious Family -- tChapter 2. The 1360 Generation -- tChapter 3. Ephebiphobia, the Fear of Youth -- tChapter 4. Streets -- tChapter 5. Walls -- tChapter 6. Learning to Endure -- tChapter 7. Precarious Iran -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Precarious Lives, Shahram Khosravi attempts to reconcile the paradoxes of Iranians' everyday life in the first decade of the twenty-first century. On the one hand, multiple circumstances of precarity give rise to a sense of hopelessness, shared visions of a futureless tomorrow, widespread home(land)lessness, intense individualism, and a growth of incivilities. On the other, daydreaming and hope, as well as civility and solidarity in political protests, street carnivals, and social movements, continue to persist. Young Iranians describe themselves as being stuck in purposelessness and forced to endure endless waiting, and they are also aware that they are perceived as unproductive and a burden on their society. Despite the aspirations and inspiration they possess, they find themselves forced into petrifying social and spatial immobility. Uncertainty in the present, a seemingly futureless tomorrow: these are the circumstances that Khosravi explores in Precarious Lives.Creating an intricate and moving portrait of contemporary Iranian life, Khosravi weaves together individual stories, government reports, statistics, and cultural analysis of art and literature to depict how Iranians react to the experience of precarity and the possibility of hope. Drawing on extensive ethnographic engagement with youth in Tehran and Isfahan as well as with migrant workers in rural areas, Khosravi examines the complexities and contradictions of everyday life in Iran. Precarious Lives is a vital work of contemporary anthropology that serves as a testament to the shared hardship and hope of the Iranian people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aIdentity (Psychology) in youthxEconomic aspectszIran. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in youthxPolitical aspectszIran. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in youthzIran. 0aYouthzIranxSocial conditions. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aFolklore. 4aHuman Rights. 4aLaw. 4aLinguistics. 4aMiddle Eastern Studies. 4aPolitical Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2017z9783110548242oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229369240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293692423Coveruhttps://